what does this command do: ssh -i "~/UserKey.pem" -C -L 25900:localhost:5900 user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com
The "ssh -i "~/UserKey.pem" -C -L 25900:localhost:5900 user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com" command is used to establish an SSH connection from a local machine using the private key file (UserKey.pem) for authentication, and then create a secure tunnel on that connection which will forward traffic sent by other devices connected to port 5900 of ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com back to the local machine's localhost:5900 address through this tunnel.

This setup is commonly used when you need a secure way for your local development environment (where you're coding and testing) communicate with an EC2 instance, which often runs some kind of graphical interface or application that needs to be accessed from other devices on the network. 

The '-i' option specifies where ssh should look for the private key file. The 'C' flag tells SSH to run in compression mode (to reduce bandwidth usage). And finally, -L is used to specify a local port forwarding rule which forwards traffic coming into specified host and port from the remote machine through an existing TCP connection that's already set up using the secure channel.
